tructed from [[Ashlar]] gritstone with a slate roof. In 1896 the architect Sir [[Arthur Blomfield|Authur Blomfield]] redesigned the nave and the original east portico was enclosed to form the chancel. The large pediment on the facade is supported by undecorated Tuscan-style columns and is inscribed prominently with MDCCCXI. The stained glass windows include several by the Victorian designer [[Charles Eamer Kempe]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://buxtonparish.org.uk/our-churches/st-johns-church/|title=THE CHURCH OF ENGLAND Buxton Team Parish {{!}} St. John the Baptist Church|website=buxtonparish.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Morten|first=David|title=Buxton in 50 Buildings|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2018|isbn=9781445678948|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSt John's Church became the town's new [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] church (for the growing numbers of residents and visitors, close to the popular spa baths), succeeding [[St Anne's Church, Buxton|St Anne's Church]] in Higher Buxton, which was later converted into a school. St John's initially served the parish of Fairfield until the parish of Buxton was created in 1898.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Langham|first=Mike|title=Buxton: A People's History|publisher=Carnegie Publishing|year=2001|isbn=1-85936-086-6|location=|pages=151}}</ref>\n\nThe church is used as an arts venue during the annual Buxton International Festival.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Parish status ==\nThe church is in a joint parish with\n\n* Christ Church, Burbage\n* Christ Church, King Sterndale\n* [[St Anne's Church, Buxton]]\n* St James' Church, Buxton\n* St Mary's Church, Buxton\n\n== Organ ==\nThe organ was installed by William Hill & Son of London in 1897. A specification of the organ can be found on the [[National Pipe Organ Register]].<ref>{{National Pipe Organ Register|id=N00340|access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\" responsi